and inserts into the cheek","Originates from the zygomatic bone and inserts into the angle of the mouth"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygomaticus major\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of facial expression that plays a key role in smiling. It originates from the zygomatic bone, which is located in the cheek area, and inserts into the skin at the angle of the mouth. This muscle is responsible for elevating the corners of the mouth, contributing to expressions such as smiling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the maxilla and inserts into the upper lip\u003C/strong\u003E describes the levator labii superioris muscle, not the zygomaticus major.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the mandible and inserts into the lower lip\u003C/strong\u003E describes the depressor anguli oris muscle, which is involved in frowning, not smiling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the temporal bone and inserts into the cheek\u003C/strong\u003E does not accurately describe any muscle of facial expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the frontal bone and inserts into the nose\u003C/strong\u003E describes the nasalis muscle, which is involved in movements of the nose, not the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The zygomaticus major is a muscle of facial expression that originates from the zygomatic bone.","It inserts into the skin at the angle of the mouth, contributing to smiling by elevating the corners of the mouth.","Understanding the anatomy of facial muscles is crucial for procedures involving facial aesthetics and reconstructive surgery."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64212"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T09:20:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T09:21:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10682"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78863"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},